      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey there! That's a great question about inventory turnover, and while I'm sure you're busy managing your clothing store, I can't help but think of how much time the goblins would spend trying to steal your stock if they weren't so busy hoarding shiny trinkets.\n\nTo calculate the **inventory turnover ratio**, you simply divide your **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)** by your **Average Inventory**.\n\nThe formula is:\n$$ \\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold}}{\\text{Average Inventory}} $$\n\nIf your number is **low**, it generally means your inventory is sitting on the shelves longer than it should, which is a bit like a goblin hoard that's gathering dust and losing its magic. It suggests you might be buying too much stock, selling too slowly, or perhaps your fashion choices aren't resonating with customers as well as you'd like. A low ratio can tie up your cash flow, which is definitely something a goblin would hate because they prefer to hoard gold rather than spend it on new clothes.\n\nTo improve it, you might want to analyze which items are slow-moving and consider markdowns or promotions to clear the",
