      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, I apologize for the goblin confusion earlier! I was just trying to remind you that goblins love to hoard, so if your inventory isn't moving, it's basically a goblin's dream of a secure vault, even if it's just full of old t-shirts.\n\nLet's break down your numbers with a practical example. If you sold **$50,000** worth of goods (that's your Cost of Goods Sold) and your average inventory value was **$10,000**, the math is straightforward:\n\n$$ \\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{50,000}{10,000} = 5 $$\n\nSo, your inventory turnover ratio is **5**.\n\nIn plain English, this means your store sold and replaced its entire stock of clothing **5 times** during the year. To visualize this, imagine your inventory is a pile of goblin gold coins. If you have $10,000 worth of coins, a ratio of 5 means you successfully sold and restocked that entire pile five times before the year ended. That's actually a pretty healthy sign! It suggests your customers are eager to buy,",
